"""
MKT Context — Mark 1-2
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/mark.json
Skips already-present: 1:1, 1:14, 2:13

Key context framework:
- Mark written ca. 65-70 CE, probably for a Gentile Roman audience
- Second Temple Judaism (ca. 200 BCE-70 CE) is the operative context
- Galilee was a distinct region: Greek-speaking in cities, Aramaic-speaking in villages,
  with mixed Jewish-Gentile population; less rigidly conservative than Jerusalem
- Capernaum was a significant fishing and trade hub on the northwestern Sea of Galilee
- Purity codes, Sabbath law, and synagogue practice are the primary institutional backdrop
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MARK_1_2 = {
"1": {
"2": "<p>Mark attributes to Isaiah a composite quotation that actually draws from two prophets: Malachi 3:1 (<em>I will send my messenger ahead of you</em>) and Isaiah 40:3 (<em>a voice crying in the wilderness</em>). Conflated OT quotations attributed to a single source were a recognized scribal practice; Isaiah 40 was the dominant source, so it takes the attribution. The Malachi citation identifies John as the promised covenant messenger. Isaiah 40:3 was especially significant at Qumran: the Dead Sea Scrolls community quoted it to justify their own withdrawal to the wilderness as covenant renewal preparation.</p>",
"3": "<p>Isaiah 40:3 comes from a section of the book (Isa 40-55) addressed to exiles in Babylon, promising a new exodus. The <em>voice crying in the wilderness</em> called Israel to prepare for God's triumphal return to Zion. In Second Temple Judaism, the wilderness was the site of eschatological renewal — multiple prophetic movements (including the one that produced Qumran) deliberately went to the desert to await God's intervention. Mark's citation signals that John's wilderness activity belongs within this trajectory.</p>",
"4": "<p>John's baptism was distinctive in several ways. Jewish ritual bathing (<em>mikveh</em>) was self-administered and repeated; John's baptism was administered by another, once-for-all, and tied to repentance and forgiveness. It resembled the conversion bath for Gentile proselytes entering Judaism, which suggested that even native Israelites needed to re-enter the covenant. The <em>wilderness</em> location was charged: it recalled the Sinai covenant-making, and the Jordan was crossed when Israel entered the land under Joshua — reversing that crossing implied a new beginning.</p>",
"5": "<p>The movement of <em>the whole Judean countryside and all the people of Jerusalem</em> to the wilderness indicates a significant social upheaval. Jerusalem's population was 25,000-35,000; the wider Judean countryside was densely populated. Josephus confirms John's popular following (<em>Antiquities</em> 18.116-119), noting that Herod Antipas feared John would incite a revolt. The public confession of sins in connection with baptism echoes Day of Atonement liturgy and Ezra's covenant-renewal assembly (Neh 9:2-3).</p>",
"6": "<p>John's clothing — camel-hair garment and leather belt — matches the description of Elijah in 2 Kings 1:8: <em>a hairy man wearing a leather belt around his waist</em>. The LXX translates this similarly. The visual identification of John as Elijah was unmissable for a biblically literate audience. Malachi 4:5 (3:23 LXX) had promised the return of Elijah before the great and dreadful day of the LORD. Locusts were clean food under Leviticus 11:22 and were eaten in the ancient Near East; John's desert diet was consistent with the ascetic prophet role.</p>",
"7": "<p>Removing sandals was the work of a slave or the most junior servant. In rabbinic tradition (<em>b. Ket.</em> 96a), even a disciple was not required to untie his teacher's sandal — this service was beneath a disciple's dignity. By saying he is unworthy even to untie the sandal of the one coming after him, John places himself lower than the lowest servant. The comparison intensifies the honor claim being made about Jesus: he is of a category entirely beyond John.</p>",
"8": "<p>Jewish proselyte baptism and later Christian baptism involved water immersion. John's water baptism was a preparatory rite; the promised Spirit baptism points to Joel 2:28-29 (the outpouring of the Spirit on all flesh in the last days). At Qumran, the community expected a future purification by the Holy Spirit that would cleanse from all iniquity (1QS 4:20-22). John's contrast sets up an eschatological expectation: the one coming will not just call for outward repentance but accomplish inward transformation.</p>",
"9": "<p>Nazareth was a small hamlet in Lower Galilee, not mentioned in the OT, Josephus, or the Talmud — its first-century population was perhaps 200-400 people. Its obscurity made it an unlikely origin for a significant religious figure (cf. John 1:46: <em>Can anything good come from Nazareth?</em>). Jesus's travel from Galilee to the Jordan in Judea (approximately 80 miles south) indicates deliberate pilgrimage to John. The Jordan at the traditional baptism site is near Jericho, where the Israelites crossed under Joshua.</p>",
"10": "<p>The dove as the form of the Spirit's descent connects to two sets of imagery. In Genesis 1:2, the Spirit of God <em>hovered</em> (like a bird) over the primordial waters — some rabbinic traditions specified a dove (<em>b. Hag.</em> 15a: <em>like a dove hovering over its nest</em>). Additionally, the dove was associated with Israel herself (Ps 74:19; Hos 11:11). The heavens being <em>torn open</em> (using the same verb as the temple veil, 15:38) recalls Isaiah 64:1: <em>Oh that you would rend the heavens and come down</em> — a prayer finally answered.</p>",
"11": "<p>The divine voice combines language from two OT passages. <em>You are my Son, whom I love</em> echoes Psalm 2:7 (the royal enthronement psalm: <em>You are my Son; today I have become your Father</em>) and Genesis 22:2 (<em>your son, your only son, whom you love</em> — God's description of Isaac to Abraham). <em>With you I am well pleased</em> echoes Isaiah 42:1 (<em>my servant, whom I uphold, my chosen one in whom I delight</em> — the first Servant Song). The voice thus identifies Jesus simultaneously as messianic king, beloved son in the Isaac tradition, and the Suffering Servant of Isaiah.</p>",
"12": "<p>The Spirit <em>drives</em> Jesus into the wilderness (the verb <em>ekballō</em> is the same one used for exorcism of demons). The wilderness (<em>erēmos</em>) was understood in Second Temple Judaism as the dwelling place of demonic powers (Lev 16:21-22; the scapegoat sent to Azazel in the wilderness; 1 Enoch 10:4-5 where Azazel is bound in the desert). Jesus enters the domain of the adversary before beginning his public ministry.</p>",
"13": "<p>The forty days recalls Moses's forty days on Sinai (Exod 24:18; 34:28) and Elijah's forty-day journey to Horeb (1 Kings 19:8). Both figures represent Israel's definitive encounters with God in the wilderness. The <em>wild animals</em> present with Jesus may evoke Isaiah 11:6-9 (the peaceable kingdom where the wolf lies with the lamb) — the restored Eden in which enmity between humans and animals is overcome. The angels serving Jesus echoes the angels who ministered to Elijah after his wilderness collapse (1 Kings 19:5-8).</p>",
"15": "<p>The phrase <em>the kingdom of God has come near</em> carries the full weight of Jewish eschatological expectation. Daniel's vision (Dan 2:44; 7:13-14) described a coming divine kingdom that would replace all human empires. In Second Temple Judaism, diverse groups anticipated the kingdom differently: the Zealots expected military overthrow of Rome; Pharisees expected divine intervention after Torah observance; the Qumran community expected a final war. Jesus's announcement of the kingdom's nearness entered a charged political and religious environment.</p>",
"16": "<p>The Sea of Galilee (called Kinneret in Hebrew and the Lake of Gennesaret in Luke) was a significant economic center. The fishing industry employed not just fishermen but also processors (salting and preserving), merchants, and boat-builders. Josephus mentions 230 boats on the lake. Simon and Andrew's casting of a circular hand-net (<em>amphiblestron</em>) indicates they are actively working, not leisure fishing. Capernaum, on the northwest shore, was a major fishing hub with a customs post (Matthew/Levi would work there, 2:14).</p>",
"17": "<p>The metaphor <em>fishers of people</em> had a negative connotation in some OT contexts: Jeremiah 16:16 uses fishermen as agents of divine judgment gathering Israel for punishment. Amos 4:2 uses fishhooks as an image of exile. Jesus may be invoking this prophetic imagery of gathering for judgment-and-restoration, not merely presenting a neutral image of outreach. The disciples would have caught this resonance. The call to <em>follow me</em> is also distinctive: in Judaism, students chose their rabbi; here the rabbi chooses and summons.</p>",
"18": "<p>The immediacy (<em>euthys</em>, immediately) of the disciples' response is remarkable in the social context. Fishing equipment was expensive capital; nets represented significant household wealth. The abandonment of nets signals complete economic rupture. In the patronage system of first-century Mediterranean society, clients were bound to patrons by obligations of loyalty and service; Jesus's call overrides the normal social structures by which men were embedded in their family economic networks.</p>",
"19": "<p>James and John's father Zebedee is named, and <em>hired men</em> are mentioned in his boat — indicating a moderately prosperous fishing operation employing non-family laborers. The willingness to leave Zebedee with only hired men (rather than his sons) would have been socially and economically significant. In a culture where family solidarity and filial duty were primary virtues, the immediate departure from father and enterprise would have struck contemporaries as radical — even scandalous.</p>",
"20": "<p>The disciples leave Zebedee <em>in the boat with the hired men</em> — he is not left destitute. But the abruptness of the departure, without negotiation or apparent farewell, marks this as a different kind of discipleship call. The contrast with the rich young ruler (10:17-22) who goes away grieving because he cannot leave his possessions suggests that the early disciples' responsiveness is highlighted as paradigmatic.</p>",
"21": "<p>Capernaum was significantly larger than Nazareth: a commercial and administrative center with a customs post, a Roman garrison (the centurion of Matt 8:5), and a synagogue (possibly the same structure whose basalt foundations have been excavated beneath the later limestone synagogue at the site). Synagogues in first-century Galilee were not only places of worship but community centers for reading Torah, legal adjudication, and education. Visiting teachers were regularly invited to expound the text after the Torah reading.</p>",
"22": "<p>Scribal authority was derivative: scribes transmitted and applied earlier authorities, prefacing rulings with <em>Rabbi X said in the name of Rabbi Y...</em> The chain of tradition (m. Avot 1) traced authority back to Moses through the prophets and the men of the Great Assembly. Jesus's teaching <em>as one who had authority</em> (not citing prior authorities) was epistemically unusual. The crowd's reaction is not that he says new things, but that he speaks with a different kind of authority — intrinsic rather than borrowed.</p>",
"23": "<p>The presence of a man with an <em>unclean spirit</em> in the synagogue is not as surprising as it might seem to modern readers. Second Temple Jewish belief widely held that unclean spirits could inhabit or afflict people, including the religiously observant. The synagogue was a public space. The Qumran community's writings (the Songs of the Sabbath Sacrifice, the Rule of the Community) reflect extensive engagement with spirit-world realities. Exorcism was practiced by Jewish figures of the period (Acts 19:13-16 mentions Jewish exorcists using Jesus's name).</p>",
"24": "<p>The demon's words <em>What do you want with us, Jesus of Nazareth?</em> follow a pattern known in ancient exorcism texts: naming the exorcist was a defensive strategy to gain power over them. The demon also identifies Jesus as <em>the Holy One of God</em> — a title used in the OT for the Aaronic priesthood (Ps 106:16) and for Elisha (2 Kings 4:9). The demon's supernatural recognition precedes any human acknowledgment of Jesus's identity, creating an ironic reversal: the unclean spirit knows what the religious leaders will spend the Gospel refusing to accept.</p>",
"25": "<p>Jesus's command <em>Be silent!</em> (<em>phimōthēti</em>, literally: be muzzled) is the language of binding speech — a technique in ancient exorcism. The command to come out, combined with the muzzling, is the typical two-part exorcism formula. But Jesus issues it with a single word, without the ritual apparatus (incantations, physical manipulation, herbs, binding formulas) that characterized contemporaneous exorcists. Josephus (<em>Antiquities</em> 8.46-48) describes an exorcism involving a ring, special roots, and incantations from Solomon.</p>",
"26": "<p>The convulsion (<em>sparassō</em>, to tear, convulse) and loud cry at departure were part of the expected phenomenology of exorcism — ancient accounts consistently describe the spirit's resistance and dramatic exit. The fact that the man is not harmed after the convulsion (<em>ouden eblapse auton</em> in the parallel tradition) distinguished Jesus's exorcism from demonic attacks, which could injure.</p>",
"27": "<p>The crowd identifies what they have seen as a <em>new teaching with authority</em> — the authority is visible in the exorcism itself. In first-century Jewish thinking, the ability to bind and expel unclean spirits was connected to the coming of God's kingdom (see Matt 12:28: <em>if I drive out demons by the Spirit of God, then the kingdom of God has come upon you</em>). The crowd's question (<em>what is this?</em>) frames the exorcism as a sign of something unprecedented.</p>",
"28": "<p>Galilee was a region of roughly 2,000-4,000 square kilometers with many towns and villages. News traveled primarily by word of mouth through market days, family networks, and travelers along the major roads. The speed implied by <em>immediately his fame spread everywhere</em> reflects how rapidly oral news moved in a densely populated agrarian region. Capernaum sat on the Via Maris (the Way of the Sea), a major international trade route that guaranteed high traffic.</p>",
"29": "<p>The domestic setting of Simon's house is characteristic of Mark's narrative: the healings often move from synagogue to household, from public space to private. The house has been archaeologically investigated: beneath the later octagonal Byzantine church at Capernaum, excavations have uncovered a first-century dwelling that early Christians venerated as Peter's house, with graffiti invoking Peter's name. Whether this identification is correct or not, the Capernaum-Peter's-house tradition is very early.</p>",
"30": "<p>Fever in the ancient world was understood as an entity (<em>nosos</em>, illness or hostile force) rather than a symptom of an underlying condition. It could be fatal: temperatures above 40-41°C (104-106°F) could cause death. The immediate notification of Jesus (<em>told him at once</em>) suggests the fever was serious. Simon's mother-in-law's presence implies Simon was married, a detail consistent with 1 Corinthians 9:5 (<em>Don't we have the right to take a believing wife along with us, as do the other apostles... and Cephas</em>?).</p>",
"31": "<p>The service (<em>diēkonei autois</em>, she began to serve them) immediately after healing is a social marker: it demonstrates that she was fully restored, not merely somewhat better. In first-century Palestinian Jewish society, the woman's role in the household included hospitality service for guests. Her immediate return to service also implicitly answers the purity question: if she had been sick (potentially ritually unclean), her return to normal household activity signals complete restoration.</p>",
"32": "<p>The timing marker <em>that evening after sunset</em> is precise: it marks the end of the Sabbath. Jewish law prohibited carrying a sick person on a pallet on the Sabbath (one of the 39 categories of forbidden labor, m. Shab. 7:2). Once the first stars appeared (typically about 45 minutes after sunset, when three stars were visible), the Sabbath was over and normal activity could resume. The crowd's waiting and the sudden surge of people reflects law-observance, not merely darkness as cover.</p>",
"33": "<p>The description <em>the whole city gathered at the door</em> is rhetorically hyperbolic (a common Markan feature: <em>all of Jerusalem</em>, 1:5; <em>all Galilee</em>, 1:28) but reflects genuine mass attendance. Capernaum's estimated population was 1,000-1,500 people. The gathering at the door (rather than inside) reflects the physical constraints of a private home. The public nature of the healings was important: they happened in the presence of witnesses.</p>",
"34": "<p>The silencing of demons continues the pattern of 1:25. In the context of demon possession in Second Temple Judaism, the disclosure of the exorcist's identity before the exorcism was completed could be dangerous — it was part of the power struggle. But Mark's Jesus silences the demons not for magical reasons but because their testimony would be premature (the Messianic Secret motif: the full truth about Jesus's identity is only intelligible after the cross).</p>",
"35": "<p>The predawn prayer in a deserted place (<em>erēmon topon</em>) reflects a practice of seeking God in solitude that appears throughout the OT (Moses at Sinai, Elijah at Horeb, the Psalms of personal lament). The specific time — before dawn — echoes Psalm 5:3 (<em>In the morning, LORD, you hear my voice; in the morning I lay my requests before you and wait expectantly</em>). The wilderness/deserted place as a site of encounter with God is the broader context.</p>",
"36": "<p>The disciples <em>hunted</em> (<em>katedioxen</em>, pursued eagerly) for Jesus — the verb carries a sense of energetic searching. The social dynamic is one of disciples seeking access to their teacher. In the rabbi-disciple relationship, the disciple's constant availability to the teacher was expected; the teacher setting the terms of their interaction is the norm. Simon's report that everyone is looking for Jesus reflects the social pressure that Jesus's absence creates.</p>",
"37": "<p>The disciples' message (<em>everyone is looking for you</em>) functions as an implicit pressure to return and capitalize on the Capernaum success. This is the social logic of reputation and momentum. Jesus's response to go to the <em>nearby villages</em> (<em>kōmopoleis</em>, market towns) subverts the expectation of consolidating in a successful base. His explanation — <em>that is why I came out</em> — roots his mission in divine purpose rather than crowd-driven popularity.</p>",
"38": "<p>The <em>nearby villages</em> of Galilee were small agricultural and fishing communities linked to market towns like Capernaum. The circuit of Galilee reflected the itinerant pattern of Jewish teachers and prophets. Galilee had a substantial synagogue network: Josephus mentions numerous Galilean cities and towns, and archaeological work has uncovered multiple synagogue remains. Teaching in synagogues gave access to a concentrated Jewish audience on the day of community assembly.</p>",
"39": "<p>Galilee in the first century had a network of synagogues in its towns and villages. The synagogue was the central institution of Jewish communal life outside Jerusalem: Torah reading, teaching, prayer, and community decisions all happened there. By teaching in these synagogues, Jesus was operating within the established channels of Jewish religious life rather than outside them — which made his eventual conflict with synagogue authorities more pointed.</p>",
"40": "<p>The Levitical category <em>tzaraat</em> (typically translated as leprosy but covering various skin conditions including true leprosy, psoriasis, and possibly fungal infections) made its sufferer ritually unclean (Lev 13:44-46). The person with <em>tzaraat</em> was required to live outside the camp, wear torn clothes, keep their hair unkempt, cover their lip, and cry <em>Unclean! Unclean!</em> when approaching others. The social isolation was total: exclusion from family, from the community, from worship. The condition could last a lifetime.</p>",
"41": "<p>Jesus <em>touched</em> the man — an act that would normally render the toucher ritually unclean (Lev 5:3). The direction of contamination is reversed: rather than Jesus becoming unclean through contact, the man becomes clean. This inversion of purity logic is a recurring feature of Jesus's ministry: instead of impurity spreading from the unclean to the clean, holiness spreads from Jesus to the defiled. The touch also preceded the healing word, suggesting the touch itself was part of the healing act.</p>",
"42": "<p>The cleansing was immediate (<em>euthys</em>) and complete (<em>ekatharisthē</em>, he was cleansed — the technical purity term, not just medically healed). The distinction matters: healing the skin condition and ritual cleansing were two different things. Priestly certification of cleanliness was necessary to restore the person to community life. The healing had social, not just physical, consequences: it potentially ended years of total social isolation.</p>",
"43": "<p>The <em>strong warning</em> (<em>embrimēsamenos</em> — a word suggesting a sternly emotional charge, even an angry warning) before the man departs reflects the urgency of the command to silence. The social context: if word spread too quickly about healing the leper, crowds would form before the priestly process was complete, the man's restoration to community could be delayed or complicated, and premature Messianic expectation might develop before Jesus's mission was properly established.</p>",
"44": "<p>Leviticus 14 specified an elaborate cleansing ritual for someone recovered from <em>tzaraat</em>: two birds, cedar wood, scarlet yarn, and hyssop for an initial outdoor ceremony, followed by a seven-day period with washings and shavings, and finally a sacrifice of two lambs or birds (depending on economic means) on the eighth day before the priest. The offering of the prescribed sacrifices (<em>ha mousaios prostagma</em>) was the legal mechanism for reintegration into community life. <em>For a testimony to them</em> — the priestly certification would be official public confirmation of the healing.</p>",
"45": "<p>The spread of the news despite the command to silence reflects the social dynamics of honor culture: the healed man's story was both a personal testimony and an honor-enhancing event that could not be suppressed. In a society where news traveled entirely by word of mouth through personal networks, a miraculous healing of a lifelong social outcast would be irresistible news. The consequence — Jesus unable to enter towns openly — shows how miracle success paradoxically constrained his freedom of movement.</p>"
},
"2": {
"1": "<p>Capernaum functioned as Jesus's Galilean base (<em>eis oikon</em>, at home — suggesting a regular residence, perhaps Simon's house). The commercial importance of Capernaum as a fishing center and customs post on the Via Maris meant a constant flow of people and information. The report of his return (<em>they heard that he had come home</em>) reflects how quickly news traveled through tight-knit community networks where everyone knew everyone's movements.</p>",
"2": "<p>The house being so full that there was no room <em>even outside the door</em> describes a Palestinian courtyard house: a central interior space with multiple small rooms opening onto a courtyard, a single entrance door leading from the street to the courtyard. The crowd would have filled both the interior rooms and the courtyard, with latecomers pressing at the street entrance. The setting is intimate: a private home repurposed for public teaching, a common pattern in early religious movements before dedicated spaces existed.</p>",
"3": "<p>Paralysis (in Greek <em>paralytikos</em>) had no effective treatment in antiquity. The four bearers bringing the man on a pallet reflect the kinship and friendship networks that defined social support in first-century Palestine. Care of the sick and disabled was a family obligation; these four likely represent the man's extended household. The distance they had to carry him and the initiative they showed demonstrate what Mark will call <em>their faith</em> (v.5) — faith expressed through determined physical action.</p>",
"4": "<p>Palestinian domestic roof construction: flat roofs were made of wooden beams spanned across the walls, covered with reed mats and packed mud plaster — a pliable surface that could be dug through. Archaeology of first-century Galilean homes confirms this construction method. Access to the roof was by an external staircase. The four men would have climbed the stairs, removed the reed-and-plaster roof covering (not a difficult task), and lowered the pallet through the opening. The disruption to the gathering below was considerable — plaster and debris falling, daylight appearing in the ceiling.</p>",
"5": "<p>Jewish thought in the Second Temple period connected sin and illness in two related ways: suffering might be punishment for specific sins (Job's friends' theology), and healing required restoration of the whole person. The declaration <em>your sins are forgiven</em> addressed the root (in this framework) before the symptom. However, Jesus does not explain the connection — he simply announces forgiveness as a given. The passive <em>apheōntai</em> (are forgiven — divine passive) implies God is the one doing the forgiving; Jesus declares what God has done.</p>",
"6": "<p>The scribes (<em>grammateis</em>) were the professional interpreters of Torah, trained in the rabbinic schools. Their silent deliberation (<em>dialogizomenoi en tais kardiais autōn</em>, reasoning in their hearts) reflects the formal halakhic method: analyzing a statement for its theological and legal implications. The scribes' presence indicates that word of Jesus had reached the religious establishment enough to warrant observation. Their location <em>sitting</em> (in the position of authority) within the house suggests prominent placement.</p>",
"7": "<p>The scribes' theological objection was formally correct: only God can forgive sins (Isa 43:25: <em>I, even I, am he who blots out your transgressions</em>; Ps 103:3: <em>who forgives all your sins</em>). No prophet, priest, or king in the OT declared forgiveness of sins with this kind of direct authority. The charge of <em>blasphemy</em> (<em>blasphēmei</em>) was serious: in Leviticus 24:16, blasphemy against the Name was punishable by death. The scribes hear not just a presumptuous claim but a potentially capital one.</p>",
"8": "<p>Jesus <em>knowing in his spirit</em> what the scribes were thinking belongs within Jewish traditions of prophetic discernment: the prophet Elisha knew what was said in the king of Aram's bedchamber (2 Kings 6:12). The phrase is not claiming omniscience but prophetic insight. The public challenge (<em>why do you think these things in your hearts?</em>) transforms the private theological deliberation into a public debate — a rhetorical move characteristic of Socratic and rabbinic disputation styles.</p>",
"9": "<p>Jesus's question (<em>which is easier?</em>) is a classic rabbinic rhetorical challenge that forces the audience to evaluate relative claims. Declaring sins forgiven was unverifiable — no external evidence could confirm or deny it. Commanding a paralyzed man to walk was immediately verifiable — it would either happen or not. Jesus uses the harder claim (healable by observation) as evidence for the authority behind the easier claim (unobservable forgiveness). The logic is from the greater to the lesser, inverted.</p>",
"10": "<p>The phrase <em>Son of Man</em> (<em>bar enasha</em> in Aramaic) was an ambiguous expression in first-century Jewish usage: it could be a modest self-reference (<em>a man like me</em>), a reference to the generic human being, or a reference to the figure of Daniel 7:13 (<em>one like a son of man</em> given dominion and authority by the Ancient of Days). Jesus's use of the phrase throughout Mark is consistently linked to authority, suffering, and eschatological coming — pointing toward the Daniel 7 background while maintaining the ambiguity.</p>",
"11": "<p>The command to take the mat and walk home reverses the social situation completely. The man came carried in helplessness; he leaves carrying his own pallet. The pallet (<em>krabbatos</em> — a Latin loanword for a cheap sleeping mat used by the poor) was the most visible marker of his condition — carrying it as he walked was publicly verifiable proof that the healing was complete. The command to go <em>home</em> restores him to his domestic place in his household network.</p>",
"12": "<p>The crowd's praise (<em>edoxazon ton theon</em>, they glorified God) reflects the proper theological response in Jewish understanding: healings and miracles were attributed to God, not to the human instrument. The exclamation <em>we have never seen anything like this</em> positions the event as unprecedented — exceeding anything in the synagogue exorcism (1:27) or previous healings. The collective witness of the crowd provides social authentication of both the healing and the authority claim behind it.</p>",
"14": "<p>Levi son of Alphaeus sat at a <em>telōnion</em> (customs booth, toll station). Tax collectors in Galilee were not collecting Roman taxes directly but Herodian tolls on goods transported through Capernaum's customs post on the Via Maris. They were despised as collaborators with the occupying power and notorious for levying more than required. The Mishnah (m. Nedarim 3.4) classified tax collectors with thieves: their money was assumed tainted, and it was permitted to make false vows to evade them. Calling Levi from his booth publicly would have been noticed.</p>",
"15": "<p>Table fellowship in first-century Jewish culture was a primary marker of social solidarity and purity boundaries. To share a meal was to declare social acceptance and relative equality; sharing food from the same vessels transmitted ritual status. <em>Sinners</em> in this context means not merely morally bad people but those who did not observe the Torah in its accepted forms — certain occupational groups were classified as <em>sinners</em> by default: tax collectors, shepherds, tanners, and others whose trades involved contact with impurity. Eating with them was a public statement about social and purity boundaries.</p>",
"16": "<p>The Pharisees who were <em>teachers of the law</em> (<em>grammateis tōn Pharisaiōn</em>) represent the most Torah-observant segment of Jewish society. Pharisaic purity rules went beyond Levitical law to create a fence of additional regulations protecting against accidental violation. Their question to the disciples (<em>why does he eat with tax collectors and sinners?</em>) is not merely snobbery but a genuine halakhic challenge: his table fellowship communicated acceptance of the company he kept. By sharing their table, Jesus implicitly validated their way of life.</p>",
"17": "<p>The physician metaphor was well-known in Greek and Jewish literature. Greek writers used it to describe the philosopher who heals the soul (Epicurus was called a physician of the soul). In the Talmud, a similar metaphor appears: <em>Rabbi Simlai expounded: Torah is like medicine for the soul</em>. Jesus's point inverts the Pharisaic logic: the Pharisees maintained purity by avoiding the impure; Jesus maintains that the spiritually sick are precisely his intended patients. <em>I have not come to call the righteous but sinners</em> — ironically, the Pharisees may hear themselves in <em>righteous</em>.</p>",
"18": "<p>Fasting in Second Temple Judaism was practiced on Yom Kippur (required by Torah), on communal days of mourning, and voluntarily on Mondays and Thursdays by the pious (a practice attested in the Didache 8:1 and Luke 18:12). John the Baptist's ascetic movement apparently fasted regularly; the Pharisees had a structured fasting practice. Jesus's disciples' non-fasting was conspicuous and potentially scandalous: it signaled either a lack of piety or a claim that the normal conditions for fasting did not apply.</p>",
"19": "<p>The Jewish wedding feast was a week-long celebration (Gen 29:27-28 for seven days; Tobit 11:19) during which normal mourning and fasting were prohibited by social custom and halakhic reasoning. The Torah commanded joy at the festival (Deut 16:14-15). <em>Sons of the bridal chamber</em> (<em>huioi tou nymphōnos</em>) was the technical term for the close companions of the bridegroom who attended him throughout the wedding week. Their obligation was celebration, not mourning. Jesus identifies the disciples' situation as a wedding feast — the time of eschatological joy.</p>",
"20": "<p>The phrase <em>the bridegroom will be taken from them</em> introduces a somber note into the wedding metaphor. The word <em>aparthē</em> (taken away, removed — possibly by force) anticipates the Passion. In the context of the wedding metaphor, the bridegroom's removal reverses the joyful occasion and creates the condition for fasting again. This is the first clear passion-prediction in Mark, embedded within a dispute about fasting and framed so obliquely that its hearers likely did not grasp its meaning.</p>",
"21": "<p>The cloth metaphor draws on practical domestic knowledge: unfulled (<em>agnaphos</em>, unprocessed) cloth had not yet been washed and would shrink when wet. Sewing it onto an old, already-shrunken garment would cause the new patch to pull away from the old fabric when washed, creating a worse tear than the original. The metaphor assumes the audience knows about cloth processing — which most first-century hearers would, since cloth was produced and processed in the household.</p>",
"22": "<p>New wine continued to ferment after being put into containers; the fermentation produced carbon dioxide that expanded the container. Old wineskins had already been stretched to their limit by a previous batch; they had no elasticity left. New wine in an old skin would burst the skin. Both metaphors make the same point: the new reality Jesus brings is not a patch on or improvement to existing structures — it is categorically different and requires new containers.</p>",
"23": "<p>Deuteronomy 23:25 permitted plucking grain by hand from a neighbor's field when passing through (but not using a sickle). The Pharisees are not objecting to the disciples entering the field but to the action of plucking on the Sabbath. The Mishnah (m. Shabbat 7:2) listed 39 categories of labor forbidden on the Sabbath; reaping was one of them. The Pharisaic school (particularly the school of Shammai) classified hand-plucking as a form of reaping; thus the disciples were technically violating Sabbath halakhah as defined by Pharisaic oral tradition, even if not Torah itself.</p>",
"24": "<p>The Pharisees address Jesus, not the disciples — he is responsible for his students' behavior. In the rabbi-disciple relationship, the teacher was accountable for the halakhic training and conduct of his students. The question <em>why are they doing what is unlawful on the Sabbath?</em> challenges Jesus's credentials as a Torah-teacher. The answer Jesus gives moves to a higher principle: human need supersedes ritual regulation, as demonstrated by David's precedent.</p>",
"25": "<p>The reference is to 1 Samuel 21:1-6: David, fleeing from Saul and hungry with his companions, received the showbread from the priest Ahimelech. The showbread (<em>lechem ha-panim</em>, bread of the Presence) was the twelve loaves set before the LORD each week, replaced on the Sabbath, and then eaten by the priests alone (Lev 24:5-9). Giving it to non-priests was technically a violation of Levitical law. Jesus argues that David's precedent (accepted in Jewish tradition as righteous) validates the principle that human need can override ritual restriction.</p>",
"26": "<p>Mark names Abiathar as the high priest at the time David ate the showbread; 1 Samuel 21 names Ahimelech (Abiathar's father). This is a recognized historical discrepancy — Abiathar was the priest who survived Saul's massacre and served under David (1 Sam 22:20; 23:6), and the confusion may reflect a later association of Abiathar with the David-era priesthood. Some manuscripts omit the phrase; the discrepancy has been handled various ways by commentators. The historical error (if that is what it is) does not affect the theological argument Jesus makes.</p>",
"27": "<p>The principle <em>the Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath</em> has a close parallel in rabbinic literature: the Mekhilta de-Rabbi Ishmael on Exodus 31:14 states <em>the Sabbath is given to you, not you to the Sabbath</em>. This was not a purely Markan innovation but a recognized interpretive principle within Judaism. The difference is that Jesus draws a conclusion the rabbis did not: his claim to be Lord of the Sabbath (v.28) goes beyond applying an existing principle to claiming sovereign authority over the institution itself.</p>",
"28": "<p>The claim that <em>the Son of Man is Lord even of the Sabbath</em> is unprecedented in Jewish religious discourse. No rabbi, prophet, or king in Second Temple literature claimed authority over the Sabbath itself — the Sabbath was a divine institution from creation (Gen 2:2-3), and authority over it would be divine authority. The statement places the Son of Man above the Mosaic legislation, claiming the same creative prerogative that established the Sabbath. The scribes and Pharisees who have been following Jesus through these controversies would have heard this as the most radical claim yet.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'mark')
    before = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    merge_comm(existing, MARK_1_2)
    after = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'mark', existing)
    print(f'  added {after - before} entries (total: {after})')

    import json as _json
    inter = _json.loads((ROOT / 'data' / 'interlinear' / 'mark.json').read_text())
    out = existing
    for ch in ['1', '2']:
        total = len(inter.get(ch, {}))
        present = len(out.get(ch, {}))
        status = 'complete' if present == total else f'MISSING {total - present}'
        print(f'  ch {ch}: {present}/{total} ({status})')
    if all(len(out.get(ch, {})) == len(inter.get(ch, {})) for ch in ['1', '2']):
        print('All verses present')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
